[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626827&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626827&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

At one point the NIC claimed it was illegal to have a machine and
domain with the same name.  I couldn't find anything about it in any
RFC.  We do it with rutgers.edu, I think several other schools do as
well.  We haven't had anyone report trouble.  However the domain name
must be your primary name.  You can't have rutgers.edu as an alias for
rutgers.rutgers.edu.  That would require that rutgers.edu have NS and
SOA records for the domain and a CNAME record for the host.  But if
you have a CNAME record you aren't allowed to have anything else.  So
rutgers.edu is the primary name and rutgers.rutgers.edu is a CNAME.

